<TITLE> Nazrul's 111th birth anniv being celebrated </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 25 (bdnews24.com)  Kazi Nazrul Islam's 111th anniversary of his birth is being observed throughout the country on Tuesday. Nazrul, born in 1899, was seen as a revolutionary poet who took the Bengali literary world by storm with his poetry that upheld the cause of the downtrodden massed. He died on August 29, 1976. People thronged the poet's grave located at the Dhaka University mosque since the morning to pay tribute to the national poet. The poet's family members laid a wreath at the grave at around 6am. Dhaka University teachers led by vice-chancellor AAMS Arefin Siddique paid floral tributes at the poet's grave. A discussion was held at the grave premises commemorating the poet. The VC said the literary works of the poet keep inspiring people even so many years after he passed away. Nazrul struggled all through his life for establishing the rights of people, particularly the downtrodden, he said. The poet's granddaughter Khilkhil Kazi recalled the times when the day was celebrated when her grandfather was alive. She said that the birth and death anniversaries of Rabindranath Tagore and Kazi Nazrul should be observed with state honour. Nazrul researcher Prof Rafiqul Islam said the mass media should bring the poet's songs and poems to the hearts of people. Language veteran Abdul Matin alleged that Nazrul had not yet been properly evaluated. The state should make arrangements to preserve the memories of the poet and spread them across the country, he said. Among other organisatons which offered tributes at the poet's grave include Nazrul Academy, Nazrul Institute, Dhaka University Teachers' Association, Nazrul Sangeet Shilpi Parisahd, Bulbul Academy of Fine Arts, Udichi, Shilpakala Academy, Awami League, BNP and their associate organisations. Awami League presidium member Obaidul Quader, joint general secretary Dipu Moni, BNP sanding committee member MK Anwar and joint secretary general Rizvi Ahmed went to the poet's grave to pay homage on behalf of their parties. Bangla Academy, Shilpakala Academy, Nazrul Institute and a number of other organisations are also holding day-long programmes to mark the occasion. President Zillur Rahman, prime minister Sheikh Hasina and opposition leader Khaleda Zia have issued special messages paying tribute to the rebel poet. Bangladesh Television and Radio and private TV channels are telecasting programmes portraying the poet's life and works. His chief works are Agnibina, Sanchita, Dolan Chanpa, Chhayanaut, to name a few. bdnews2
